estions (5 and 6), I should provide historical facts. For the instruction/placeholder lines (1-4), I should probably indicate that they are not factual queries or provide a null/empty string, or explain their nature. However, the prompt says "the value is the Factual knowledge of each question". If the "question" is an instruction, there is no factual knowledge associated with it in the context of the definition provided.\n    *Strict Adherence:* I must follow the format. I should try to provide the most relevant information possible. For the instruction lines, since they are not questions about reality, I will state that they are instructions/placeholders and do not contain factual queries, or simply return an empty string/null if appropriate. However, to be helpful and accurate to the "Factual Knowledge" definition, I should clarify that these are not factual queries. But usually, in these tasks, if the input contains noise, the model should handle it gracefully.\n    *Better Interpretation:* The user might be testing my ability to filter or handle mixed input. But the instruction says "for each element in dic... the value is the Factual knowledge". If I return empty strings for 1-4, it might be safer. But looking at the content, 5 and 6 are the actual questions. 1-4 look like artifacts from a template (e.g., "Query if [rag]...").\n    *Decision:* I will treat 1-4 as having no factual knowledge content because they are meta-instructions, but I must include them as keys. I will provide a statement indicating they are instructions rather than factual queries, or leave them empty. Given the strict JSON requirement, I\'ll provide a descriptive value explaining they are not factual queries, or just the factual answer for the real questions and a note for the others. Actually, looking at the definition "Factual knowledge is information that aligns with objective reality...", instructions do not fit. I will provide a response that acknowledges the nature of the key.\n   